NORMALISED EXTRACT
Remainder operator (%) semantics
- Operator: a % b returns the remainder after dividing a by b using integer division semantics for numeric operands.
- In JavaScript, % is the remainder operator (not modulo). It returns a value with the same sign as the dividend (left operand).
- Computation: a % b === a - Math.trunc(a / b) * b for numeric operands, where Math.trunc removes fractional part toward zero.

Edge cases and sign rules
- If a or b is NaN, result is NaN.
- Division by zero: a % 0 returns NaN for nonzero a; 0 % 0 returns NaN.
- Negative operands: example semantics:  5 % 3 === 2; -5 % 3 === -2; 5 % -3 === 2; -5 % -3 === -2.
- Non-integer numeric operands: operands are converted to numbers; remainder is computed after conversion (floating point behaviour preserved).

Assignment variants and operator precedence
- Remainder assignment: a %= b is equivalent to a = a % b except a is evaluated only once on the left-hand side per JavaScript evaluation rules.
- Precedence: % shares the same precedence group as multiplication and division; evaluate left-to-right.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Use Number.isFinite and Number.isNaN checks prior to remainder if inputs may be invalid to avoid NaN propagation.
- For mathematical modulo with always non-negative results, implement ((a % b) + b) % b to normalize to positive remainder for positive modulus b.

REFERENCE DETAILS
- Exact specification: ECMAScript numeric remainder semantics as defined in ECMA-262 (Remainder operator). Implementation formula: remainder = a - trunc(a / b) * b, with trunc toward zero.
- Practical pattern for positive modulo: function mod(a,b){const r = a % b; return (r + Math.abs(b)) % Math.abs(b);} ensures 0 <= result < |b| when b != 0.

